      <bioghist id="aspace_59af62e8015369de0803ef869f0ea89e">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>The Love Makes a Family Political Action Committee (LMF PAC) (2002-2011) worked for lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender equality in Connecticut by supporting and working for pro marriage equality candidates for elected office. It was the political action arm of Love Makes a Family (1999-2009), a Connecticut statewide coalition of organizations and individuals whose mission was to pass a second-parent adoption law; support efforts to pass a domestic partnership package for state employees; defeat Defense of Marriage Amendments (DOMAs) both to the state statute and the state constitution; and to pass a marriage equality law for same-sex couples in Connecticut. The first three goals were reached by 2000; the marriage equality law was passed in 2008. Love Makes a Family developed into three inter-related entities: LMF, Inc., incorporated as a 501(c)(4) in 2000; the LMF Political Action Committee, established in 2002; and the LMF Foundation, incorporated as a 501(c)(3) in 2006. After meeting its goals through community education, grassroots organizing, and legislative advocacy and lobbying, LMF, Inc. and LMF Foundation disbanded in 2009. The Love Makes a Family Political Action Committee disbanded in 2011.</p>
      </bioghist>
      <relatedmaterial id="aspace_28480fd0b95343bd4d80e688a500e297">
         <head>Related Materials</head>
         <p>Love Makes a Family Records (MS 1962).</p>
      </relatedmaterial>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_05959c8ce2a4ac9c2a6992ff20928f08">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The records document the administration, communications, finances, and endorsements of the Love Makes a Family Political Action Committee. It contains correspondence, committee files, meeting agendas and minutes, and information on the committee's political endorsements (print and electronic). The collection contains responses to questionnaires created by the Love Makes a Family Political Action Committee and sent to political candidates in Connecticut to assess their positions on marriage equality and other LGBT rights issues.</p>
      </scopecontent>
      <accessrestrict id="aspace_d9ad39bcd6a63dfdba6c0e151f3598d9">
         <head>Conditions Governing Access</head>
         <p>The materials are open for research. Original computer files may not be accessed due to their fragility. Researchers must consult access copies.</p>
      </accessrestrict>
